<br>
My hair used to be just above my shoulders; it's stick straight and very very thick.  Well, I went to a place asking that they turn it into a graduated bob, the kind that's pretty popular at the moment.  And I have my little requirements, like no electric trimmers and that my hair has to be chipped into instead of being cut straight across.  If they cut it straight across, it is very very obvious on my hair.  The stylist then proceeded to cut my hair into many garish straight-cut layers in the back and left my front hair in longer layers.  It was too late to correct it.  When I asked her what she had thought she was doing, she replied that she thought this would look better.  It looked TERRIBLE!<br>
<br>
I wound up getting a pixie crop (at a different place) to fix it.   Now it's taking me forever to grow it out because everytime I go in for a trim, I come out with my hair back at it's starting length.  Despite telling them to cut off no more than a 1/2&quot;.  They just get carried away with the trimming, each and every time.  Very frustrating.<br>
<br>
So now I just cut it myself while I'm growing it out.  The only part of my hair that really bothers me is the nape of my neck, which tends to grow at a faster rate than everywhere else.  Since I don't want a mullet <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.mywhimsy.com/boards/dvicons/smlyWink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> , I just grab a pair of scissors, twist little sections of hair and then shred into it.  It does the job of creating a chipped looking cut and I've gotten pretty decent at making the entire line look relatively straight.     <br>
<br>
Anyhoo, I ramble lots.  But regarding your cut, hair does grow back, so it never hurts to get a second cut at a good place to fix it.  A really good stylist can take what you have and make little adjustments to make it look a billion times better.<br>
